\begin_layout Subsection
Image registration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the most simple case,
 image registration consists in identifying a geometric transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 that will put in correspondence the pixels of a reference image 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 with thoses of a moving image 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A classical formulation is as follow:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{T} & =\underset{T\in\mathcal{T}}{\text{argmin}}\mathcal{D}\left(I_{1},T(I_{2})\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 is the space of possible transforms,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is a measure of the difference between the reference image and the transformed image.
 The general workflow for the registration of two images is given in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Workflow_Registration_Images"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The main 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

components
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the workflow are the geometric transform,
 the metric for comparing the registered shape or image to the reference,
 and the optimisation algorithm for identifying the transform that generates the best metric.
 In the case of image registration,
 it is also necessary to interpolate one (or both) of the images in order to compute the metrics.
 
