\begin_layout Subsection
Shape Registration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider here shapes as geometric data,
 such as point sets,
 polygons,
 or polygonal meshes.
 Various specialized algorithms have been developed for the registration of geometric data.
 One of the most common ones is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Iterative Closest Point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Besl_1992_pami"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The image registration workflow may anyway be applied to the transformation of geometric shapes.
 The main differences consist in the metrics,
 and in the fact that it is not necessary to resample the transformed shapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Computational anatomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concepts of computational anatomy were developed during the 80's,
 mostly following the works of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grenander_Miller_1998_QAM"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The idea is to compute an average image or shape based on a collection of individual subjects.
 The approach implementations usually differ depending on the nature of the data (image or geometric shapes).
\end_layout

